ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Tide at Craster Cove", body:`
<p>Martha had promised their mother two things: that they would be back before five, and that they would not, under any circumstances, go beyond the rope barrier at the mouth of Craster Cove. She had kept the first promise for eleven years of her life. The second lasted less than an hour.</p>
<p>"It's only a cave," said Douglas, ducking beneath the frayed rope as though it were nothing more than a skipping rope held too low. "Caves don't belong to anyone."</p>
<p>Martha hesitated, glancing back along the empty beach. The tide was far out, a thin silver line stitched to the horizon, and the wet sand shone like polished pewter. Surely ten minutes could do no harm. She followed her brother into the dark.</p>
<p>Inside, the cave smelled of salt and old seaweed. Douglas's torch swept over walls glistening with damp, and picked out a ledge high above them where something pale gleamed. "Bones!" he whispered gleefully, though on closer inspection it proved to be nothing more sinister than a bleached driftwood branch.</p>
<p>It was the sound that warned Martha first — a low, hollow boom, like a door closing in a distant room. She turned. Where the cave mouth had framed a wide picture of sand, there was now a shifting sheet of grey water. The tide, which had seemed so lazily distant, had crept behind them like a thief.</p>
<p>"Douglas," she said, keeping her voice steady, "we're leaving. Now."</p>
<p>The water was knee-deep at the entrance and shockingly cold, tugging at their legs with an impatience that frightened her far more than the depth. Douglas stumbled; Martha gripped his wrist and hauled him forward, remembering, absurdly, a school assembly about rip currents that she had barely listened to at the time.</p>
<p>When at last they staggered onto dry sand, soaked to the waist, Douglas began to laugh — the wild, shaky laughter of someone who has been more afraid than he will ever admit. Martha did not laugh. She was looking at the rope barrier, snapping in the rising wind, and thinking about promises, and how quickly the sea takes back what people borrow from it.</p>`});

