ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Secret Life of Honeybees", body:`
<p>To most of us, a honeybee is little more than a passing hum on a summer afternoon. Yet inside every hive operates one of the most sophisticated societies in the natural world — a bustling city of up to sixty thousand residents, in which every citizen has a job and no one is ever unemployed.</p>
<p>At the centre of this city is the queen. Contrary to popular belief, she does not rule; she is less a monarch than a factory, laying up to two thousand eggs a day in the summer months. The true decision-makers are the workers — all of them female — who progress through a strict career ladder as they age. A young worker begins as a cleaner, scrubbing empty cells until they gleam. Later she is promoted to nurse, feeding larvae, then to builder, producing wax from glands on her abdomen. Only in the final weeks of her short life does she graduate to the most dangerous job of all: forager.</p>
<p>Foragers may travel more than three miles from the hive in search of nectar, and it is here that the honeybee performs its most astonishing trick. When a forager discovers a rich patch of flowers, she returns to the hive and performs what scientists call the waggle dance — a figure-of-eight movement whose angle and duration tell her sisters the precise direction and distance of the food. She is, in effect, drawing a map with her own body.</p>
<p>The males, known as drones, lead easier but shorter lives. They do no foraging, no building and no cleaning; their sole purpose is to mate with a new queen. When autumn arrives and food grows scarce, the workers show little sentimentality: the drones are driven from the hive to perish in the cold.</p>
<p>Honeybees matter to humans for a simple reason: roughly one third of the food we eat depends on pollination, much of it carried out by bees. When a bee ferries pollen from blossom to blossom, she is not being generous — she is simply gathering food — yet the accidental gift she leaves behind keeps orchards fruiting and fields flowering. The next time you hear that hum on a summer afternoon, it may be worth remembering that you are listening to one of agriculture's hardest workers, commuting home from a three-mile shift.</p>`});

