ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Station Clock", body:`
<p>September, 1940. The train had taken all day, stopping and starting through countryside that grew steadily greener and emptier, and Thomas had long since eaten the fish-paste sandwiches his mother had wrapped in brown paper that morning. Around his neck, on a loop of string, hung a cardboard label with his name printed on it, as though he were a parcel that might otherwise go astray.</p>
<p>The platform at Netherfold was smaller than any station he had ever seen — a single lamp, a wooden bench, and a large white clock whose hands stood at six exactly. The other evacuees were collected one by one: the Hartley twins by a farmer's wife with flour on her apron, and little Joan Pickles by the vicar, who carried her suitcase as if it were made of glass. Soon only Thomas remained, sitting beneath the clock with his gas-mask box on his knees.</p>
<p>He counted the minutes. Ten past. Quarter past. In London, at this hour, his street would be filling with the smell of a hundred suppers, and his mother would be pulling the blackout curtains across the windows. He swallowed hard and stared fiercely at his boots, because eleven-year-olds from Bermondsey did not cry on strange platforms.</p>
<p>At twenty-five past six, a bicycle clattered against the station railings and a tall woman strode onto the platform, cheeks pink, grey hair escaping from beneath a man's flat cap. "Thomas Ellery?" she called, in a voice that could probably be heard two fields away. "I'm Mrs Cartwright. I'm afraid my pig got out, and a pig waits for no one." She looked him up and down, taking in the label, the box, the tightly held cap. "Well," she said, more gently, "you look half-starved and three-quarters miserable. We can mend both."</p>
<p>She took his suitcase before he could object and marched out to the lane, where a second bicycle — a rusty one, with a basket — leaned against the hedge. "Can you ride?" she asked. Thomas, who had never owned a bicycle but had borrowed every one in his street, nodded. "Good lad. It's two miles, mostly downhill, and there's rabbit pie at the end of it."</p>
<p>And though the ache of home did not leave him — it would not leave him for many months — Thomas found, as the hedges rushed past in the last of the light, that it was surprisingly difficult to feel entirely wretched while freewheeling downhill towards a rabbit pie.</p>`});

