ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"Urban Foxes: Neighbours in the Night", body:`
<p>At around two o'clock in the morning, when the last takeaway has closed and the buses run empty, the true owners of many British streets emerge. A dustbin lid shifts; a shadow slips along a garden wall; a pair of amber eyes catches the glow of a streetlamp. The red fox, once a creature of woodland and farmland, has become one of the most successful city dwellers in the country.</p>
<p>Foxes first moved into British towns in significant numbers during the 1930s, when new suburbs — with their large gardens, hedges and railway embankments — spread into the countryside. Rather than retreating, the foxes simply stayed put, and discovered that urban life suited them remarkably well. A city fox rarely needs to hunt in the way its rural cousins must. Instead, it dines on an extraordinary menu: discarded chips, windfall apples, earthworms pulled from lawns after rain, and food deliberately left out by admiring householders. Researchers who examined the stomach contents of urban foxes found that over half their diet comes, directly or indirectly, from humans.</p>
<p>Not everyone welcomes these bold neighbours. Gardeners complain of dug-up flowerbeds and stolen shoes — foxes are notorious collectors of footwear, which they carry off not to eat but seemingly to play with. Others object to the eerie scream of the vixen on winter nights, a sound so human that it is regularly reported to the police. Supporters, however, point out that foxes provide free pest control, consuming large numbers of rats and mice, and that attacks on people are vanishingly rare.</p>
<p>Perhaps the most remarkable thing about urban foxes is how quickly they have adapted. Studies show that city foxes are bolder than rural ones, willing to approach within metres of humans, and that some have learned the timing of bin collections in their territory. One Bristol fox, fitted with a tracking collar, was found to check the same fifteen gardens each night in a regular circuit, like a postman doing his round in reverse — collecting rather than delivering.</p>
<p>Love them or loathe them, urban foxes are here to stay. They ask for no permission and pay no rent, yet they were using these hills and hollows long before the streets were laid over them. It may be more accurate to say that we moved in with the foxes, rather than the other way around.</p>`});

