ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Clockwork Sparrow of Milliner's Lane", body:`
<p>Everyone on Milliner's Lane agreed that old Mr Fetterling was peculiar, though nobody could agree on precisely how. The baker said he had once seen him feeding biscuit crumbs to a pigeon and apologising to it for the weather. The schoolmistress said his shop — WATCHES & AUTOMATA, REPAIRS UNDERTAKEN — had not sold a single watch in twenty years. What everybody knew for certain was that his window display never changed: one dusty carriage clock, one velvet cushion, and a small brass sparrow with folded wings.</p>
<p>Ada passed the shop every morning on her way to school, and every morning the sparrow's glass eye seemed to follow her. On the last day of term, unable to bear the mystery a moment longer, she pushed open the door. A bell jangled somewhere in the dimness, and the smell of oil and metal shavings rose to meet her like a tide.</p>
<p>"Ah," said Mr Fetterling, appearing between towers of cogs and mainsprings, "the girl who looks. Most people only glance." He lifted the sparrow from the window with hands as gentle as a nurse's, wound a hidden key three times — no more, no less — and set it on the counter.</p>
<p>What happened next Ada would remember for the rest of her life. The brass wings unfolded with a whisper of sliding metal. The head tilted. Then the sparrow opened its beak and sang: not a tinny mechanical jingle, but a true dawn song, liquid and full, as if a summer morning had been captured, folded very small, and hidden inside the metal chest.</p>
<p>"It took me eleven years," said Mr Fetterling quietly. "Four hundred and six pieces. People ask me why I never sell it." He shut one eye and peered at Ada through a jeweller's lens, as if she too were a mechanism whose quality he was judging. "I don't keep it because it is valuable. I keep it because everyone who hears it looks the way you look now — and that expression, young lady, cannot be bought in any shop in England."</p>
<p>Ada floated home with her head full of brass feathers. She did not yet know that she would one day be apprenticed in that dim, ticking shop, nor that the sparrow would one day be hers. For now, it was enough to have heard a summer morning singing in December, on a grey little street where nothing was ever supposed to happen.</p>`});

