ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Race to the South Pole", body:`
<p>In the summer of 1910, two ships slipped out of European harbours, both bound — though only one crew knew it — for the same square of ice at the bottom of the world. Aboard the Terra Nova was Captain Robert Falcon Scott of the British Navy, leading a large expedition of scientists, ponies and motor sledges. Aboard the Fram was the Norwegian Roald Amundsen, who had told almost nobody, not even most of his own crew, where he was really going. Only when it was too late to turn back did he send Scott a telegram of chilling politeness: "Beg leave to inform you Fram proceeding Antarctic."</p>
<p>The two leaders could hardly have been more different. Amundsen had spent years living with the Inuit peoples of the Arctic, learning to drive dog teams, to wear loose furs that trapped warm air, and to travel light and fast. Scott placed his faith in ponies, which sank in the snow and suffered terribly in the cold, and in experimental motor sledges, one of which fell through the ice before the journey had even begun and the rest of which broke down within days.</p>
<p>Amundsen's party of five, with fifty-two dogs, left their base on 19 October 1911 and moved with astonishing efficiency, laying supply depots and covering more than twenty miles on a good day. On 14 December 1911 they stood at the South Pole, where they planted the Norwegian flag and — in a gesture that mixed courtesy with cold triumph — left a tent containing a letter for Scott and a note asking him to forward it to the King of Norway, in case they did not survive the return.</p>
<p>Scott's five-man team, hauling their own sledges through soft snow, arrived thirty-four days later, on 17 January 1912. The sight of the Norwegian flag met them like a blow. "Great God!" Scott wrote in his diary. "This is an awful place and terrible enough for us to have laboured to it without the reward of priority."</p>
<p>The return journey became one of the most famous tragedies of exploration. Weakened by hunger, cold and scurvy, Scott's men died one by one; the final three, including Scott himself, perished in their tent in late March, just eleven miles from a depot of food and fuel. Yet in defeat Scott achieved a strange kind of victory: the diaries found beside his body, full of courage and devotion to his comrades, made him a legend, while the meticulous Amundsen — who had, after all, simply done everything right — was long remembered with respect rather than love.</p>`});

