ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Lighthouse Keeper's Daughter", body:`
<p>The storm had been building all afternoon, and by nightfall it flung itself against the Longstone lighthouse as though it meant to tear the rock from the sea. Inside, Grace pressed her face to the salt-blurred glass and watched the waves climb higher than she had ever seen them. Her father, the keeper, had long since lit the great lamp; its beam swung out into the dark, catching the rain in silver sheets.</p>
<p>It was Grace who saw the wreck first. As the beam wheeled round, it lit, for half a second, the broken shape of a steamship dashed upon the rocks a quarter of a mile away. Clinging to what remained of the deck were a handful of survivors, so small against the black water that they might have been mistaken for seabirds.</p>
<p>"We must go to them," Grace said.</p>
<p>Her father shook his head. "No boat could live in that sea. And even if it could, the two of us could never row against it."</p>
<p>But Grace had already taken down the oars. She was not a large girl, nor a strong one, but she had rowed these waters since she was six years old, and she knew that if they waited for the storm to pass there would be no one left to save. Reluctantly, her father followed her down to the little cove where their rowing boat was moored.</p>
<p>What followed was an hour Grace would never fully be able to describe. The boat rose and fell like a leaf on a waterfall; twice it was nearly swamped; her arms burned until she could no longer feel them. Yet somehow, between them, they reached the wreck, dragged four half-drowned survivors aboard, and fought their way back to the lighthouse, where Grace's mother wrapped the shivering strangers in every blanket they owned.</p>
<p>When news of the rescue reached the mainland, Grace Darling became, quite against her wishes, the most famous young woman in the country. Poems were written about her; strangers sent her gifts; artists begged her to sit for portraits. But Grace never understood the fuss. She had seen people in danger and had done what needed doing. That, to her, was not heroism. It was simply what the daughter of a lighthouse keeper was for.</p>`});
