ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"How Volcanoes Work", body:`
<p>Beneath the solid ground on which we walk lies a world of astonishing heat. Only a few dozen miles down, the temperature is high enough to melt rock into a thick, glowing liquid called magma. Most of the time this molten rock stays trapped far below the surface. Occasionally, however, it finds a way out — and when it does, the result is a volcano.</p>
<p>The Earth's outer shell is not a single unbroken layer. Instead it is cracked into enormous pieces, rather like the cracked shell of a boiled egg, and these pieces — called tectonic plates — drift very slowly across the molten rock beneath. Most volcanoes form at the edges of these plates. Where two plates pull apart, or where one is forced down beneath another, magma can rise through the gaps and cracks towards the surface.</p>
<p>As magma rises, gases trapped inside it begin to expand, exactly as the bubbles in a fizzy drink expand when you unscrew the cap. If the magma is thin and runny, these gases escape gently, and the volcano oozes slow rivers of lava that people can sometimes outwalk. But if the magma is thick and sticky, the gases become trapped until the pressure is enormous — and then the volcano erupts with terrifying violence, hurling ash, rock and gas miles into the sky.</p>
<p>Volcanoes have long been feared, and with good reason: a single large eruption can bury entire cities, as happened to the Roman town of Pompeii in AD 79. Yet volcanoes also give as much as they take. The ash they scatter breaks down over centuries into some of the richest farming soil on Earth, which is why people continue to live and grow crops in their shadow. Volcanic rock is used for building; volcanic heat is tapped to make electricity; and it was volcanoes, erupting over billions of years, that helped create the very atmosphere we breathe.</p>
<p>Today, scientists called volcanologists keep constant watch over the world's most dangerous volcanoes, measuring tiny earthquakes, swelling ground and escaping gases for the warning signs of an eruption. They cannot yet stop a volcano — no one can — but by predicting when one may erupt, they can give people the most precious gift of all: enough time to escape.</p>`});
