ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Boy Who Drew Machines", body:`
<p>In the small town of Vinci, in the hills of Italy, there once lived a boy who could not stop asking questions. Why did birds not fall from the sky? How did water know to flow downhill? What lay behind the blue curtain of the horizon? His name was Leonardo, and while the other children played, he filled sheet after sheet with drawings of everything he saw: swirling water, the veins of a leaf, the muscles of a horse's leg.</p>
<p>Leonardo's notebooks were unlike anyone else's. He wrote from right to left, in mirror writing that could only be read by holding the page up to a looking-glass — perhaps to keep his ideas secret, perhaps simply because he was left-handed and it came more easily. Between the lines of writing crawled the strangest inventions: a machine with beating wings that a man might strap to his back and fly; a horseless cart that moved by itself; a diving suit for walking on the seabed; even a device very like the helicopter, three hundred years before anyone built an engine that could lift one.</p>
<p>Most of these machines were never made. The materials of Leonardo's time were too heavy, and the power to drive them did not yet exist. His flying machine would never have left the ground. Yet this hardly seems to matter. What Leonardo truly possessed was not the ability to build, but the ability to imagine — to look at a bird and see, hidden inside it, the secret of flight; to look at the world as it was and picture the world as it might one day become.</p>
<p>He was, of course, also one of the greatest painters who ever lived. But it would be a mistake to think of Leonardo as a painter who happened to like machines, or an inventor who happened to paint. To him there was no difference. Studying how light fell on a curved surface made him a better engineer; understanding how muscles moved made him a better artist. The world, to Leonardo, was a single glorious puzzle, and every subject was simply another window onto the same great mystery.</p>
<p>Five hundred years later, we still open his notebooks and marvel. Not because he gave us working machines — he did not — but because he reminds us of something easy to forget: that curiosity, followed far enough, is a kind of genius all its own.</p>`});
