ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Last Train Home", body:`
<p>Priya knew she had cut it fine. The clock above the station entrance read 11:52, and the last train left at 11:55. She flew down the steps two at a time, her bag thumping against her hip, and burst onto the platform just as the guard raised his whistle to his lips.</p>
<p>"Wait!" she gasped. "Please!"</p>
<p>The guard, a round man with kind eyes and an enormous moustache, paused, looked at her, and lowered the whistle. "In you get, then. Quick about it." Priya tumbled through the nearest door, and with a hiss and a lurch the train began to move.</p>
<p>The carriage was almost empty. An elderly woman dozed in one corner beneath a tartan blanket; a young man in paint-spattered overalls stared out of the window; and near the middle sat a small girl of perhaps seven, entirely alone, clutching a battered cardboard suitcase and swinging her feet, which did not quite reach the floor. It was the girl who caught Priya's attention, because she was crying — not loudly, but in the silent, hopeless way of someone who has been crying for a long time and no longer expects anyone to notice.</p>
<p>Priya hesitated. It was late; she was tired; it was, strictly speaking, none of her business. Then she thought of how she would feel, seven years old and alone on a night train, and she crossed the carriage and sat down opposite the child.</p>
<p>"That's a very fine suitcase," she said. "Where are you off to?"</p>
<p>The girl looked up, startled, and wiped her nose on her sleeve. "Grandma's," she whispered. "But I got on the wrong train, and now I don't know where I am, and the man said this train doesn't stop at Grandma's station." A fresh tear rolled down her cheek.</p>
<p>Priya's heart turned over. But she smiled, and kept her voice light and certain, the way her own mother used to. "Well, then," she said, "it's lucky you met me, because I happen to be extremely good at finding grandmas. The very first thing we'll do, when we reach the next station, is telephone yours. Now — does she keep a cat, this grandma of yours? Because grandmas with cats are always the easiest to find."</p>
<p>The girl gave a small, wet laugh. And though the night outside was black and the train rushed on into the dark, the distance to Grandma's house suddenly seemed a great deal shorter than it had a moment before.</p>`});
