ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Great Migration", body:`
<p>Every year, across the plains of East Africa, one of the most extraordinary events in the natural world unfolds. More than a million wildebeest, together with hundreds of thousands of zebra and gazelle, gather into a single vast herd and begin an enormous journey in search of fresh grass and water. This is the Great Migration, and it never truly ends: the animals travel in a great circle, roughly a thousand miles around, following the rains from one grazing ground to the next, year after year, for as long as anyone can remember.</p>
<p>The journey is far from easy. The herds must cross wide rivers where crocodiles, some of them older than the oldest person in a nearby village, lie waiting beneath the muddy water. They must run the gauntlet of lions, cheetahs and hyenas, who follow the migration as a travelling market follows a crowd. Tens of thousands of animals die each year — the old, the sick, the very young and the merely unlucky. Yet still the herd moves on, because to stop is to starve.</p>
<p>Why do they do it? The answer lies in the rain. East Africa has two rainy seasons and two dry ones, and grass grows only where the rain has recently fallen. No single patch of land can feed a million wildebeest for long. By keeping constantly on the move, the herd is always arriving at fresh pasture just as the grass there is at its greenest, and leaving just as it runs out. The migration, in other words, is not a journey with a destination. It is the destination — an endless loop, tuned over countless generations to the rhythm of the rains.</p>
<p>The wildebeest themselves seem unremarkable animals: ungainly, awkward-looking creatures that early European visitors unkindly described as if assembled from the spare parts of nobler beasts. But there is a deep intelligence in the herd as a whole. No leader gives the order to move; instead, the decision seems to ripple through the entire group at once, as though a million animals shared a single mind. Scientists call this 'swarm intelligence', and they still do not fully understand it.</p>
<p>Watching the migration, it is impossible not to feel that one is witnessing something very ancient — a pattern of movement older than farming, older than cities, older than history itself. The wildebeest have been walking this circle since long before there were people to watch them. Long after us, in all likelihood, they will be walking it still.</p>`});
