/* ---------------- PAPER 12 ---------------- */
ENG_PASSAGES.push({title:"The Inheritance", body:`
<p>When old Mr Abernathy died, he left his entire fortune — and it was a considerable one — to be divided between his two nephews. But the will contained a peculiar condition. The money would go, it said, to whichever of the two young men could fill a large empty barn 'most completely, at the least expense', using whatever he chose. They would have one day each, and the lawyer would judge.</p>
<p>The elder nephew, Marcus, was a practical sort, and he set about the task with energy. He hired three carts and spent the whole day hauling load after load of straw from a neighbouring farm, until the barn was stacked to shoulder height and the air was thick with golden dust. It had cost him a good deal of money, and by evening he was exhausted, but he surveyed his work with satisfaction. Surely, he thought, no one could fill the barn more fully than that.</p>
<p>The younger nephew, Jonah, arrived the next morning empty-handed, and the lawyer raised an eyebrow. Jonah asked only that the great barn doors be shut, and that every crack and window be covered until the building was as dark as midnight. Then, from his pocket, he produced a single small candle and a box of matches. He struck a match, lit the candle, and held it up. At once, warm light welled into every corner of the barn, filling the whole vast space from floor to rafters, leaving not one shadow untouched.</p>
<p>"You asked me to fill the barn most completely and at the least expense," said Jonah quietly. "Straw fills only the space it takes up. But light fills everything, and touches every corner at once — and it has cost me a single candle."</p>
<p>The lawyer looked from the towering, costly heap of straw to the small, steady flame that had somehow filled the entire barn, and he closed his book. The fortune, he declared, belonged to Jonah — not because he had been the more hardworking, for plainly he had not, but because he had understood something his brother had missed: that the cleverest answer to a problem is rarely the most obvious one, and almost never the most expensive.</p>
<p>Marcus, to his credit, laughed aloud when he understood, and shook his brother warmly by the hand. "I filled the barn with my back," he admitted. "You filled it with your head. I can hardly complain that the better man won."</p>`});
